    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-1855731">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-1855731">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,1855731)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-1855731">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/aelanna" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(334454); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=334454&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610227291" alt="Aelanna" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=334454)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/aelanna" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(334454); return false;" >Aelanna</a></span> <span class="odate time_1379700340 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">20 Sep 2013 18:05</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1855731">
									

<blockquote>
<p>Dr. Thaddeus Xyank is a character whose story I have already begun to establish elsewhere on the site (See <a href="/iteration-0">Iteration 0</a> and <a href="/the-deep-end">The Deep End</a>).</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I realize this, and that's irrelevant. Supplements should not contain attributes because they need to belong to the main page, not the satellites. SCP articles should not contain <em>orientation</em> because they apply specifically to tales. If you want this to be cataloged as an orientation, <em>then it needs to be a tale</em>.</p>
<p>The simple question is whether this page is intended to be critical to the understanding of SCP-1780 itself. It if, on its own, is not <em>absolutely critical</em> to that purpose, then it shouldn't have been made a <em>supplement</em> in the first place, and I'm perfectly fine with that.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>It also is written, quite clearly, in the style of a Welcome Letter, meant for general distribution among newly recruited members of RCTF-Δt. It is definitely an orientation by its very nature.</p>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>orientation</strong> <em>n.</em> [&#8230;] 3. an introduction, as to guide one in adjusting to new surroundings, employment, activity, or the like: <em>New employees receive two days of orientation.</em></p>
</blockquote>
<p>The dictionary &#8212; and the common usage of the term &quot;orientation&quot; in the context of either new employees or freshmen students &#8212; says otherwise.</p>
<hr />
<p>None of this is directed at you or the quality of your work. This is site infrastructure maintenance, and is not up for debate or subject to author creative license. The site index and archives needs the tags as such, and that's all there is to it.</p>

							</div>

								
					
